Explanations regarding global competitiveness
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Harvard University Center for International Development published the Global Competitiveness Report (GCR) for the year 2001.
In the study that encompasses 75 countries, Finland, the United States, and Canada occupy the first three places, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe come in last.
(All ranking lists can be read at www.weforum.com.)
As a co-leader of this annual study, I am often asked what competitiveness actually means.
Is there also an economic competition among the countries in addition to the military one?
Is it even meaningful to say that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is defined with great precision: namely, as the ability of a country to achieve sustainable economic growth over the medium term—thus, within a period of five years.
This definition, however, does not mean that the competitiveness of one country simultaneously says something about missing competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries of the world could simultaneously achieve higher growth.
Nevertheless, it is sensible to create a ranking of countries in terms of their growth potential.
Every country is interested in finding out whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep up with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In some ways, economic growth can be compared to a sporting competition where the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
For example, countries compete for internationally mobile capital.
The more foreign direct investment a country can attract, the less investment another country gets.
This becomes completely clear when countries apply for a specific investment project.
When Intel plans a new semiconductor fabrication plant, different countries are invited to submit offers.
The competition for the contract is tough, and frequently bids also include tax breaks, infrastructure improvements, and even adjustments to the local technical university's study plans.
This year, we assessed the competitiveness (growth potential) of a country using three broad criteria: (1) Technology, (2) public institutions, and (3) macroeconomic stability.
For each of these categories, we determined indicators whose average values were calculated using a specific method to then create a general growth and competition index.
The criterion of Technology refers to a country's ability to drive new developments and to adopt technologies that have been developed elsewhere.
Some countries like the USA, Japan, Korea, Israel, and Sweden invest strongly in research and development and thereby achieve high values in the area of innovation.
Other countries like Argentina and Brazil invest less in research and development and therefore achieve little in terms of new products and processes.
Innovation-loving countries also enjoy a high prosperity due to these innovations.
In this category, the USA, Canada, and Finland occupy the first three places on the ranking list.
The criterion "public institutions" refers to the quality of administration.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts unbiased and impartial?
Can one trust that the government will fulfill its obligations properly?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and corrupt judges.
High ethical standards enhance economic performance.
In this regard, the Nordic countries are globally leading, and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark also top the ranking.
Corruption is virtually unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced government budget, a realistic exchange rate of the national currency, the ability of companies and the government to obtain loans on the capital market, and high confidence that the government will fulfill its financial obligations.
Using Asia in the late 1990s as an example, we have learned that a macroeconomic crisis can undermine economic growth, even if the companies are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries regarding macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the world economy can be divided into two categories of countries: those that are innovation-friendly and those that are not innovation-friendly.
Only about 20 countries actively engage in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the wealthiest in the world, an excellent system of technological innovation is considered a prerequisite for continuous competitiveness.
The universities must be outstanding, state laboratories should have world-class standards, and the government and industry should strongly invest in research and development.
A key factor for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who pursue higher education and universities after completing compulsory schooling.
In the United States and Canada, this share amounts to 80%.
For the "non-innovation-friendly" countries, technology is just as important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed within the country itself.
Some countries are good at importing new technologies, while others are less so.
In the past ten or fifteen years, a significant portion of technology imports occurred within the framework of foreign direct investments.
American companies that invested heavily in Mexico, or Taiwanese firms that invested in mainland China, brought in new technologies that boosted production efficiency in the respective target country's economy.
Therefore, it was certainly sensible for the affected countries to strive with great enthusiasm for these foreign investments: they bring not only capital but also new technologies.
A strength and at the same time a weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is oriented towards the medium term and does not focus on the next one to two years.
Our rankings are not suitable for assessing short-term cyclical changes in a national economy, but they do provide insight into the long-term prospects of the major economies.
It is therefore an irony that many of the countries that placed first this year, such as the USA or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while other countries ranked further back, such as China (ranked 39), are not affected by the global recession.
Part of the slowing of the economy is linked to the terrorist attacks on September 11, but it is also increasingly clear that the American economy and other economies connected to it via trade and production networks were already sliding into recession before September.
Nevertheless, we believe that this is a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the USA will regain its ability to achieve strong economic growth over the next five years.
